Looking at version `4.17.15`. 
The implementation of `arrayPush` in `lodash.core` is
```
function arrayPush(array, values) {
  array.push.apply(array, values);
  return array;
}
```

Unfortunately. `array.push.apply` throws a `Range error` in Chrome when the source array has more than ~130k elements:
```
[].push.apply([], Array.from({ length: 200000 }).map(() => 'a'));
```
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/35681649/74317597-67294080-4d84-11ea-9587-b945a62a5b85.png)

Firefox starts to throw at about 600k elements: 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/35681649/74317653-7b6d3d80-4d84-11ea-83cd-5ab3fcc53a95.png)

 

The implementation in `lodash` main is:
```
function arrayPush(array, values) {
    var index = -1,
        length = values.length,
        offset = array.length;

    while (++index < length) {
      array[offset + index] = values[index];
    }
    return array;
  }
```
which does not crash in browsers when pushing very long arrays.

The following should be false rather than true:

```ts
const a = /foo/g;
const b = /foo/g;
a.lastIndex = 1000;
_.isEqual ( a, b ); // => true, it should be false
```

For 2 reasons:

1. If the `lastIndex` property is different those 2 regexes may have very different behaviors.
2. `_.clone` accounts for the `lastIndex` property and copies it over, so for consistency `_.isEqual` should account for it too.

lodash defines the type `isMatchWithCustomizer` as the third argument of the method `isMatchWith`.

The return type of this callback function is defined as a `boolean`, but I believe the correct definition should be `boolean | void`.

Intended or not, the function `isMatchWith` can be used in following fashion:

```
const obj1 = {
    _id: 1,
    someProp: [{
        _id: 1034,
        value: 10
    }]
};

const obj2 = {
    _id: 2,
    someProp: [{
        _id: 1537,
        value: 10
    }]
};

_.isMatchWith(obj1, obj2, (value, other, indexOrKey) => {
    if (indexOrKey === '_id') return true;
});
```
In this example, I use the callback function to check if `indexOrKey` is the id of the object, and if it is, I return `true`, because for this comparison the equality of the id is irrelevant.

As for the other properties, I need lodash to perform the default `isMatch` comparison, but also ignoring any nested `_id`, and that's exactly what happens when nothing (or `undefined`) is returned from that function.

Everything works, but only if I'm allowed to return `undefined` in that callback, which I'm not.

In case this was not the expected behavior of the method `isMatchWith`, and I'm essentially exploiting an unintended behavior, please, close this issue.

